description: Expansion of Product (1 - x^k)^8 in powers of x.
comments: Number 22 of the 74 eta-quotients listed in Table I of Martin 1996.Denoted by g_4(q) in Cynk and Hulek in Remark 3.4 on page 12 as the unique level 9 form of weight 4.This is a member of an infinite family of integer weight modular forms. g_1 = A033687, g_2 = A030206, g_3 = A130539, g_4 = A000731. - _Michael Somos_, Aug 24 2012a(n)=0 if and only if A033687(n)=0 (see the Han-Ono paper). - _Emeric Deutsch_, May 16 2008Cubic AGM theta functions: a(q) (see A004016), b(q) (A005928), c(q) (A005882).
references: Newman, Morris; A table of the coefficients of the powers of $\eta(\tau)$. Nederl. Akad. Wetensch. Proc. Ser. A. 59 = Indag. Math. 18 (1956), 204-216.

formula: Expansion of q^(-1/3) * eta(q)^8 in powers of q.Expansion of q^(-1/3) * b(q)^3 * c(q) / 3 in powers of q where b(), c() are cubic AGM theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Nov 08 2006Expansion of q^(-1) * b(q) * c(q)^3 / 27 in powers of q^3 where b(), c() are cubic AGM theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Nov 08 2006Euler transform of period 1 sequence [ -8, ...].a(n) = b(3*n + 1) where b(n) is multiplicative and b(3^e) = 0^e, b(p^e) = (1 + (-1)^e)/2 * (-1)^(e/2) * p^(3*e/2) if p == 2 (mod 3), b(p^e) = b(p)*b(p^(e-1)) - b(p^(e-2))*p^3 if p == 1 (mod 3) where b(p) = (x^2 - 3*p)*x, 4*p = x^2 + 3*y^2, |x|<|y| and x == 2 (mod 3). - _Michael Somos_, Aug 23 2006Given g.f. A(x), then B(x) = x * A(x^3) satisfies 0 = f(B(x), B(x^2), B(x^4)) where f(u, v, w) = v^3 - u * w * (u + 16 * w). - _Michael Somos_, Feb 19 2007G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (9 t)) = 81 (t/i)^4 f(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t). - _Michael Somos_, Sep 29 2011G.f.: Product_{k>0} (1 - x^k)^8.a(2*n) = A153728(n). - _Michael Somos_, Sep 29 2011a(4*n + 1) = -8 * a(n). - _Michael Somos_, Dec 06 2004a(4*n + 3) = a(16*n + 13) = 0. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 19 2005A092342(n) = a(n) + 81*A033690(n-1). - _Michael Somos_, Aug 22 2007Sum_{n>=0} a(n) * q^(3*n + 1) = (Sum_{i,j,k in Z} (i-j) * (j-k) * (k-i) * q^((i*i + j*j + k*k) / 2)) / 2 where 0 = i+j+k, i == 1 (mod 3), j == 2 (mod 3), and k == 0 (mod 3). - _Michael Somos_, Sep 22 2014
